<br>
&quot;When will we buy oil in euros?&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, not anytime in the forseeable future. Europe likes to pride itself on it's Not America stance, and that's one of the reasons its not embraced universally by the world financial community. America is a large, stable, economically powerfully nation, with very few problems with capital, resources, supply, or management. Disagree with our politics all you like, but to debate our economic superiority at this time makes you look like a fool with an agenda.<br>
<br>
What a gem of an article you posted:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.observer.co.uk/business/story/0,6903,900867,00.html">www.observer.co.uk/busine...67,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;So the US can carry on printing money - effectively IOUs - to fund tax cuts, increased military spending, and consumer spending on imports without fear of inflation or that these loans will be called in. As keeper of the global currency there is always the last-ditch resort to devaluation, which forces other countries' exporters to pay for US economic distress. It's probably the nearest thing to a 'free lunch' in global economics&quot;<br>
<br>
This entire article is premised on the fact that the US is in some kind of economic distress making it safer for investors to back oil purchases with Euros. This also assumes that the Euro is doing well based on better economic management and not some kind of wishful thinking that this combined currency will hopefully dominate the US dollar.<br>
<br>
OK, let's look at the current distress the US is in. One of my favorite reports involving the federal debt is <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.tcf.org/publications/Basics/Balanced_Budget/Preface.html" target="top">this one</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> from The Century Fund. Its straightforward and easy to read. Its data only goes to 1996, but the deficit has only improved since then until 2002 so that favors this reports conclusion even more.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;How do we compare to other countries?<br>
<br>
Government spending and the federal deficit seem relatively modest when compared, as a percentage of GDP, to the outlays and shortfalls of other nations. As a percentage of GDP, the United States' total governmental deficit—consolidating state and local budgets with the federal budget—is the smallest of any major industrialized country.17 (See Figure F.) Also, total tax collections in the United States as a percentage of GDP, counting state and local as well as federal levies, are also lower than in most other developed nations.(See Figure G.) And total government debt in the United States is about average when compared to the big seven OECD countries. (See Figure H.)&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.tcf.org/publications/Basics/Balanced_Budget/images/budfigf.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.tcf.org/publications/Basics/Balanced_Budget/images/budfigg.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.tcf.org/publications/Basics/Balanced_Budget/images/budfigh.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Especially interesting is the middle chart showing if we taxed as high as Germany or France we would all be saying &quot;what debt?&quot; because it would be paid off already. The first chart also shows that according to France and Germany even higher deficit spending seems to be the way to go. The third chart just shows that our debt is basically on average with other major producers. People forget that half the staes in the US have budget surpluses. This money pays for alot of infrastructure that the Federal government doesn't have to. Small Eurpoean nations only wish they had this extra money floating around.<br>
<br>
This idea that our trade imbalance is some how a &quot;bad thing&quot; stems from the fact that because the dollar is so strong it's harder to export and make a profit of compete with European countries. As the euro grows stronger, it will only make it easier to export to europe and harder for europeans to make a profit in the US. Hmmm, strong dollar or more exports? It's win - win.<br>
<br>
The idea that capital flowing into the US is somehow bad is laughable. It just shows international confidence in the strength and the future of the U.S. economy. Foriegn capital helps that multinationalism that people like Shehbahn seem to be so corcerned that the US doesn't do. So which is it? Multinationalism or Keeping Foreign Captial Out? Make up your mind please. Europeans seem to be at home with <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.eu-datashop.de/download/EN/sta_kurz/thema4/np_03_03.pdf" target="top">foreign controlled companies</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. What's good for the goose... etc, right? Personally, I like the idea that the US is such a free market that foreigners feel confident in owning US companies. It keeps them vested in making sure our future is secure. On the flip side if their currency takes a nose dive like the Yen did, they will scramble to sell US companies back to the US at a tremendous bargin for US investors. Anyone remember when people speculated that Japan was going to dominate the US economically? Nowdays that thought is the punch line to a joke.<br>
<br>
Now I'll just throw out some numbers out:<br>
<br>
EU15 population: ~375 million<br>
EU15 GNP in PPP/capita: $20,166<br>
EU15 GNP: ~$7.5 Trillion<br>
EU15 Unemployment: 7.7%<br>
<br>
USA population: ~290 million<br>
USA GNP in PPP/capita: $30,586<br>
USA GNP: ~$9 Trillion<br>
USA Unemployment: 5.7%<br>
<br>
SO, while the EU has potential (as would a North American combined dollar) it currently lacks any incentive for investors to stop backing oil trades with dollars. Why would investors leave the hugely popular and stable US currency and move to an unstable and untested currency whos internal struggles among members are well documented? The article you posted was overly optimistic and basically just wishful thinking on the part of the author, who's anti-american agenda is clear.<br>
